Fig. 11
 shows the spectra for the Sn - CD composite 0.05 g L−1 and the pure Sn film after contact with the 3.5% NaCl medium for 24 h. For the high-resolution spectrum of the composite, the contribution of two Sn 3d species with binding energies at 485.58 and 486.92 eV is noted, referring respectively to the Sn–C (9.37%) and Sn2+ (90.63%) oxidation states, presenting predominantly the Sn2+ state (Table 6
). On the other hand, the pure Sn coating presented the contribution of only Sn 3d species, corresponding to an energy of 486.64 eV, referring to Sn+2. Regarding C1s, the high-resolution spectrum of the composite exhibits a different profile from that observed in Fig. 6, showing the contribution of four species with binding energies of 284.3, 285.28, 286.95, and 288.95 eV. Zhou et al. 2024, studied nickel and carbon quantum dot composites, suggesting a protection mechanism for CDs by computational chemistry. According to this study, CDs interact chemically with the chloride in the medium, in which the carbon p orbitals hybridize with the chloride p orbitals, preventing the permeation of this ion into the film bulk. The XPS results of this work (Fig. 11 and Table 6) suggest that CDs changed the behavior of the Sn film in the saline medium. The composite coating showed a less oxidized surface, with two Sn 3d species with energies of 485.58 (9.37%) and 486.92 eV (90.63%). However, the protection mechanism of CDs should be further studied [13,34,42].
